{"/service/ndnp/ndhi/batch_ndhi_hebron_ver01/data/sn85042414/00295863468/1920100501/0048.xml":{"full_text":"I#\nI\n1\nS\n'''i'^',-\u00bbf#.!\nv:\nEVENING EDITION.\nThomas Wilton Declares This\n-Is A Means Qf Keeping\nTragic Economic Results\ntracted Toward Normal\nA Conditions. ,r/\nS A?\nis\n\u00bbv\"\nTOir\nr?\nifi\nCourageous and Optimistic .VJ|\n_, Morale Necessary to Check\nTrouble When Prices Drop\nWhen Industrie* Art Con-\n1\nBoston, Oct. S-\u2014\"Can American in\ndustry- be contracted toward .lormul\ndimensions without' tragic economic\nresults V*r\nAn affirmative answer to this quea\nBon was made public here yesterday\nafternoon by the leader and offlci&J\nSpokesman .of the largest industry\nthe United States when Thomas\nE. wllson, president of the Institute\nof American Meat Packers, told in\nvestment bankers froni all sections of\nthe country that \"every essential busi\nness rendering a genuine service, no\nmatter how serious Its problem, may\nface the future with abiding confi\ndence.\"\nMr. Wilson, speaking on '\"The Gen\neral Industrial Situation\" before the\nInvestment.. Bankers' Association of\nAmerica, dealt frankly with declining\nprices, shrinking inventories, closing\nof punts, careless rumors of panic\nand industrial collapse and other fac\u00ad\nInterest From the 1st\nEveryone should maintain jjwr-\n1\nF7'/\ntors In the current industrial outlook.\nHe said in. part:\n\"The pressing necessity of .the pres\nent is to maintain. a courageous and\noptimistic morale. The descent from\nthe heights of abnormal production\nto the normal levels of peace times\nshould be reached by gradation and\nnot by perperidicular drops: No in\ndustry upon which large bodies of\nlabor are dependent for a. market for\ntheir ra^ material has a moral right\nto close Its doors in such a time as\nthis merely to prevent a shrinkage\nin accumulated surplus or for the\npurpose of limiting production so as\nto create artificial values for ma\nterials on hand. To do so ip to take\nadvantage of extraordinary conditions,\nthe burden eg which should be shared\nby all. I am glad to say that we\nhave had. but few such examples.\"\nAt another point, Mr. Wilson said:\n\"Timid men have asked the ques\ntion, 'Can American industry which\nwas expanded to record proportions\nunder the forced draft of war neces\nsities be. contracted toward normal\ndimensions without 'tragic economic\nresults?' Representing as I do, prob\nably the largest industry.in the coun\ntry and taking a philosophical view of\nthe present and a hopeful outlook for\nthe future, I feel that the question\ncan be answered in the affirmative.\nThere may be pessimists here and\nthere who are apprehensive that' only\na panic can result from the extraor\ndinary world conditions created by\nthe war. In my opinion, such a catas-\nDeposits made in our Saving's Depart\nment on or before the 5th are entitled\nto interest from the 1st.\nBRING IN YOUR DEPOSIT NOW\nInterest is compounded quarterly.\nWe allow interest for every calendar\nmonth money is on deposit.\nNo withdrawal restrictions.\nSmall as welt as large deposits are in\nvited. fy :/v, -V\n8 Youna Bulls for Sale\nThese bulls are all registered Hoistein\nmonths to 2 years old.\nftJ'\nA,\nThey are sired by Sir Ppntiac OIKe, Gcand Champion at Min\nnesota State Fair in 1918 or by King Wason Segis Star, lately sold\nfor $5000. Both of these bttUs have great milk and butter records,\ntheir sisters haying, broken hundreds of world's records in the past '.Vj^\ntwo years.\nThe bulls offered for sale were all raised at Lilac Hedge and are\n\"North Dakota acclimated.\n\"V t\" ft I \"V 5 1\nV*i tf 1\nHEAD YOUR HERD WITH ONE OP THESE\nMQRTGAGE LIFTERS.\n*\"*4 i! 4 Jw-' -'Jfi***' is? 4V' 5^\nIpf\nJERRY D. BACON S SON)' Wl\ntrophe is not probable so long as the\ntrue American spirit continues to an\nimate our institutions.\"\nNo Great Shortage.\nIn discussing the Industrial situa\ntion as it exists today/ Mr. Wllson\ndeclared that there is \"no shortage\nof raw material sufficiently serious\nto curtail production below normal\nrequirements.\"\n\"Most manufacturers,\" he added,\n\"are fairly well supplied /with orders\nfor their products, notwithstanding\nsome cancellations. Transportation\nfacilities show steady improvement.\"*\n\"The process of readjustment is now\nin fall motion/' Mr. Wilson declared.\n\"The manufacture Of luxuries Is be\ning curtailed. The spending fever is\nabating. Commodity prices are de\nclining and further deflation seems\nto be tn progress. A recent survey\nhas been made of the industrial con\nditions of our country which fhows\nthat economically the United States\nis better off than any other country\nof the world.\nFavorable Reports.?\n\"Favorable crop reports come from\nevery section. While declining prices\nhsivo* caused some disappointment, yet\ngenerally speaking the farmers are\nin a sound economic position. The\nproducers of live stock have been\nmore seriously affected by declining\nmarkets than any other branch of\nfarm activities. There is little evi\ndence of idleness throughout the\ncountry, except In a few localities.\nBo far as the distribution of labor\nis concerned, the situation nationally\n\"appears to be well equalised with the\nexception of temporary shortage of\nunskilled labor ifi some of the agri\ncultural regions.\n\"While money is still tight, it\nshould not continue so Indefinitely.\nThere Is great encouragement to be\nranging from 6\n..PW\".\nW.\nSi.:1 j,\nDakota\nV.^K-V-'\n\"4.\nGRAND FORKS HERALD, TUESDAY, OCTOBER 5, 1980j\nI\n\u00ae1\nBRYAN AMONG DELEGATES AT MEET OF CONGRESS AGAINST ALCOHOLISM\n\"Mmm\n4\nof delegates to Fifteenth International Congress Against AlcoltoHsra. Arrow points to W. J. Bryan.\nW. J. Bryan is one of the commanding figures at the Fifteenth International Congress Against Alco\u00ad\nholism, now in session at Washington, D. C. Delegates from every civilized country are present. They agree\nthat the world is going dry, but diff er as to the time it will take, the more pessimistic setting the date fifty\nyears hence, the optimists predicting a dry world by 1930.\ndrawn 'from the fact that there has\nbeen no substantial decrease in bank\ndeposits during the last few months.\nIndividual saving accounts show\nmarked improvement. This seems\nto indicate a movement toward thrift,\nand that the period of rccklcss and\nextravagant spending is past. Dis\ncounting of bills by industrial con\ncerns appears to be very general. The\nbusiness outlook appears to be good\nin nearly every section. The survey\nshows that a shortage of coal andr a\nfailure to increase individual produc\ntivity appear to be the only unfavor\nable aspects of the immediate indus\ntrial situation.\"\nSome Bad Problems.\nMr. Wilson stated that labor has\nhad some difficult problems to solve\nand \"some grave internal difficulties\nto overcome,\" and added:\n\"It has been disturbed by a radical\nminority seekilig to revolutionise in\ndustry and to overthrow many of the\ntime-honored traditions of American\ninstitutions. The thoughtful conser\nvative forces of labor seem to be in\nthe ascendancy and will no doubt\nBoaooe (\"Fatty\") Arbuckle tn\n\"The Bound-Vn\"\nA\nGeorge H. KaUord production\nA PARAMOUNT PICTUBE\nEnid Bennett in\n\"Ber Bueband'a PrienA\"\nA PABA1SOVHT PIOTVBB\nBiUle Burke In\n\"Prisky\nVbtu,\n:iiS\u00a7\nJohnson\"\nA FABAMOTTKT PXOTUBB\nBthel Clayton in\n\"A City Sparrow\"\nA PABAXOUmr PIOTVBB\nBthel Clayton In\n\"Sins of Boeanne\"\nA PABAltOUBT PIOTVBB\nA Cosmopolitan Production\n\"Kmnoreaauo\"\nA PABAKOVBT PIOTUBB\nA Cosmopolitan Produetlaa.\n\"The Beetl\u2014 Sex\"\nA PABA3KOUBT PZCTVBB\nDorothy Xtaiton In\nC'Sadf An Sou\"\nBorotby Mlton in\n\"A Bomantle A*rentureeaw\nA PABAMOUJT PIOTUBB\nOeeU B. BeMUIa'a Production\n\"Something to Think About?'\nA PABAKOVBT PIOTVBB\nft\nftfj\nse-4'S\nire Show\nat the\nlead to a sound and patriotic adjust\nment. of this great problem. Labor\nis beginning to realize that, if it .is\nto profit permanently by the increases\nin wages which it has received, it\nmust increase the value and purchas\ning power of the sum added to the\npay envelope by lowering the cost\nof commodities through increased\nproduction. Labor and industry\nshould recognise that their interests\nare mutlally dependent and should\nendeavor to co-operate in the solution\nof their problems. Autocratic man\nagement of industry on one side with\na militant, bitter and class conscious\norganization of labor on the other\nside, will no. longer be supported by\npublic opinion, and where such a con\ndition exists, it presents a problem,\nthe solution of which must be found.\nIf the men who represent all grades\nand kinds of business and labor in\nthe United States could unite in a\nmovement not to fight each other,\nbut firmly to expose the omissions of\nleach and fairly spread the truth,\nthey might find a common ground\nfor ee-operation and turn the whole\n.A\ntrend of events toward a more arnica*\nble solution of their eonwnon prob\nlems.\nAs indicating the extent of the aft\ner-war adjustments which some in\ndustries ^have effected and.which oth\ners are still facing, Mr. Wilson re\nvealed the tremendous changes in live\nstock production and meat packing.\nKxportf? Dccreasc.\n\"For example,\" he said, \"durlnfr the\nmonth of March, 1913, the United\nStates exported only 770,392 pounds\nof fresh berf. In March, 1918, it ex\nported 62.064,261 pounds, or more\nthan 80 times that much. In March,\n1920 those figures had shrunk to 6,\n036,166 pounds, or only about one\ntenth of the quantity exported in the\n{Continued on page 14.)\nE\n313\nDeMers\nIT IS WITH THE GREATEST PLEASURE\nTHAT THE MANAGEMENT OF THE\nTRAND THEATE\nANNOUNCES\nThat They Have Purchased the Entire Program of\n1920-21 Paramount Pictures\nAmong the Productions to Be Shown\nThis Fall and Winter are the following:\nElsie Perguaon In\n\"lady Bose'a Daughter\"\nA PABAKOVBT PZCTVBE\nOeozge Pitzmanrloe'a Produetion